    accent: "#c8c0a0", servings: 4,
    description: "A whole gilt-head bream encased in a thick shell of coarse salt mixed with egg whites and herbs, baked until the salt crust is set hard. When cracked at the table, the fish inside is perfectly steamed, extraordinarily moist, and lightly seasoned by the surrounding salt — never salty.",
    pairings: ["Pistou Provençal", "Rosé de Provence", "Chablis", "Lemon Vinaigrette"],
    children: [],
    ingredients: [
      { value: 1, unit: "piece", name: "Whole sea bream (daurade), 1kg, gutted but not scaled" },
      { value: 1500, unit: "g", name: "Coarse sea salt" },
      { value: 4, unit: "piece", name: "Egg whites" },
      { value: 3, unit: "sprig", name: "Fresh thyme" },
      { value: 3, unit: "sprig", name: "Fresh rosemary" },
      { value: 2, unit: "piece", name: "Bay leaves" },
      { value: 1, unit: "piece", name: "Lemon, sliced (to stuff cavity)" },
      { value: 3, unit: "tbsp", name: "Fresh fennel fronds" },
    ],
    steps: [
      { title: "Prepare the salt crust", body: "Beat egg whites to a light froth. Combine with coarse salt and mix until it resembles damp sand. The egg white binds the salt and helps it form a rigid crust. Add some of the herbs to the salt." },
      { title: "Stuff the fish", body: "Season the cavity lightly. Stuff with remaining herbs, lemon slices, and fennel fronds. The cavity aromatics will perfume the fish as it steams." },
      { title: "Encase in salt", body: "Spread one-third of the salt mixture on a baking tray in the outline of the fish. Lay the fish on top. Cover completely with the remaining salt, pressing firmly to adhere. The fish should be completely sealed with no gaps." },
      { title: "Bake until the crust is solid", body: "Bake at 200°C/400°F for 30–35 minutes. The salt crust will turn beige and completely solid. The fish inside steams in its own moisture." },
      { title: "Crack tableside", body: "Bring to the table. Crack the crust with a heavy spoon or small hammer — theatrically. Carefully peel back the crust. The skin of the fish lifts with the salt; the flesh beneath is moist and perfect. Portion and serve." },
    ],
    tips: "Do not panic about the fish being too salty — the salt crust seasons only the surface of the fish and the skin acts as a barrier. A scaled fish would absorb more salt through the exposed flesh; an unscaled fish is better protected.",
