    description: "The defining pastry of the French pâtisserie counter: an elongated choux tube filled with chocolate or coffee pastry cream, iced with chocolate fondant in a shining stripe. The éclair is the daily work of every pâtissier — its quality reveals the kitchen's standard more nakedly than any elaborately decorated cake.",
    pairings: ["Café Noir", "Café au Lait", "Espresso", "Earl Grey"],
    children: [],
    ingredients: [
      { value: 125, unit: "ml", name: "Water" },
      { value: 125, unit: "ml", name: "Whole milk" },
      { value: 100, unit: "g", name: "Unsalted butter" },
      { value: 140, unit: "g", name: "All-purpose flour, sifted" },
      { value: 4, unit: "piece", name: "Eggs" },
      { value: 0.5, unit: "tsp", name: "Fine sea salt" },
      { value: 500, unit: "ml", name: "Whole milk (for pastry cream)" },
      { value: 5, unit: "piece", name: "Egg yolks (for pastry cream)" },
      { value: 100, unit: "g", name: "Granulated sugar (for pastry cream)" },
      { value: 50, unit: "g", name: "All-purpose flour (for pastry cream)" },
      { value: 80, unit: "g", name: "Dark chocolate, melted (for pastry cream)" },
      { value: 300, unit: "g", name: "Dark chocolate fondant or ganache (for icing)" },
    ],
    steps: [
      { title: "Make choux paste and pipe éclairs", body: "Make the choux paste (bring water, milk, butter, and salt to a boil; beat in flour; cool; beat in eggs gradually until smooth and glossy). Pipe 12cm logs onto lined baking trays using a 1.5cm round nozzle. Bake at 200°C for 25–28 minutes without opening the oven." },
      { title: "Make chocolate pastry cream", body: "Make standard pastry cream with milk, yolks, sugar, and flour. Off heat, whisk in melted dark chocolate. Chill completely. Beat until smooth before using." },
      { title: "Pierce and fill each éclair", body: "Pierce 2 holes in the base of each éclair with a skewer. Pipe chocolate pastry cream through the holes using a small round nozzle — the éclair is done when the cream begins to emerge from the second hole." },
      { title: "Ice with chocolate fondant", body: "Warm chocolate fondant to 38°C — pourable but not runny. Dip the top of each éclair in the fondant, smoothing with a finger. Work quickly — fondant sets in seconds." },
      { title: "Set and serve at room temperature", body: "Allow fondant to set completely — 15 minutes. Éclairs are best eaten at room temperature the day they are made." },
    ],
    tips: "The secret to a crisp choux éclair is drying during the baking: the last 5 minutes should be with the oven door slightly ajar to allow steam to escape. Closing the oven prematurely produces soft, soggy choux that collapses.",
